1
00:00:12,459 --> 00:00:15,501
I trust everyone's GDC is treating them wonderfully.

2
00:00:15,521 --> 00:00:20,063
I hope you took some time off work this week to actually digest all the stuff you're learning.

3
00:00:21,084 --> 00:00:26,487
So you're here for Finding Character Voice with Your Voice, and lucky you, this talk

4
00:00:26,647 --> 00:00:27,368
is virtual.

5
00:00:27,828 --> 00:00:31,951
Back when I planned on doing it in person, there was going to be some audience participation,

6
00:00:32,031 --> 00:00:33,932
so yeah, you dodged a bullet.

7
00:00:34,793 --> 00:00:38,835
Anyway, if people still hashtag, you can use the hashtag vocalwriting.

8
00:00:40,058 --> 00:00:42,880
All right, so what are we learning today?

9
00:00:43,200 --> 00:00:46,003
Well, there's only one point I'm really here to make,

10
00:00:46,063 --> 00:00:48,184
and that's that adding vocal performance

11
00:00:48,224 --> 00:00:50,806
in the writer's room can add depth to your characters,

12
00:00:51,047 --> 00:00:51,967
whether they're voiced or not.

13
00:00:52,428 --> 00:00:54,309
I mean, just look at Gordon Freeman here.

14
00:00:54,369 --> 00:00:55,890
He doesn't have a lot to say vocally,

15
00:00:55,991 --> 00:00:58,533
but he says things with his face,

16
00:00:58,593 --> 00:01:00,334
at least that's how I interpret it.

17
00:01:01,155 --> 00:01:03,396
So why are you even listening to me?

18
00:01:04,112 --> 00:01:10,233
Well, my name is Cyrus Nemadi, and at one point here at GDC not too long ago, I was

19
00:01:10,333 --> 00:01:12,474
probably begging you for voice acting jobs.

20
00:01:13,134 --> 00:01:16,695
Some of you said yes, and so I've had a lot of fun doing voice acting for games.

21
00:01:17,055 --> 00:01:18,575
You can see some of the titles I've been in.

22
00:01:18,675 --> 00:01:21,856
You may have heard me in Hades last year.

23
00:01:21,916 --> 00:01:23,996
It was, yeah, that was a good game.

24
00:01:24,176 --> 00:01:24,756
It was a good game.

25
00:01:25,676 --> 00:01:28,877
I won't do the voices now, but perhaps I can be convinced.

26
00:01:29,938 --> 00:01:37,062
I've since transitioned into writing full-time because there is such a thing as a guaranteed

27
00:01:37,523 --> 00:01:38,543
full-time writer.

28
00:01:39,044 --> 00:01:43,467
The hustle is tough as a voice actor, so please hug your voice actors.

29
00:01:44,047 --> 00:01:44,828
They work hard.

30
00:01:45,668 --> 00:01:50,171
I'm a lead writer for June's Journey and Tropic Cats at Wooga, where we develop narratively

31
00:01:50,211 --> 00:01:51,072
driven mobile games.

32
00:01:52,008 --> 00:01:56,900
It's done pretty well for us as it happens, because a good story and good characters,

33
00:01:57,160 --> 00:02:00,889
surprisingly, well, not surprisingly at all, keep the audience coming.

34
00:02:02,262 --> 00:02:05,985
So, most of us are here to make characters.

35
00:02:06,725 --> 00:02:07,906
It's kind of daunting, isn't it?

36
00:02:08,466 --> 00:02:12,409
Creating a fully fleshed out, believable, sentient being

37
00:02:12,469 --> 00:02:15,811
from absolutely nothing but our own imaginations.

38
00:02:15,951 --> 00:02:18,113
That's intense.

39
00:02:18,553 --> 00:02:20,755
It sounds really impressive when I put it like that.

40
00:02:21,355 --> 00:02:22,896
So, how do we do it?

41
00:02:23,677 --> 00:02:26,619
Well, there are a few basic necessities

42
00:02:26,659 --> 00:02:27,839
to understanding a character.

43
00:02:28,673 --> 00:02:32,075
You can get the gist from a description, some keywords, and imagery.

44
00:02:32,795 --> 00:02:34,316
This is a character from Tropicats.

45
00:02:34,817 --> 00:02:40,360
We've got some basic descriptors, a minor bit of backstory, and the character art that

46
00:02:40,400 --> 00:02:40,981
we settled on.

47
00:02:41,661 --> 00:02:46,024
From there we can get a start on writing dialogue from this character's perspective, but

48
00:02:47,401 --> 00:02:48,942
This isn't a lot of information.

49
00:02:49,002 --> 00:02:51,605
There is so much about this cat that we don't know.

50
00:02:52,245 --> 00:02:57,650
We want to give our characters depth, but how can we possibly create something with

51
00:02:57,710 --> 00:03:03,876
a real personality and history without knowing their life story or lore, for lack of a better

52
00:03:03,916 --> 00:03:04,076
word?

53
00:03:04,782 --> 00:03:07,725
And you may ask yourself, does my character just need more lore?

54
00:03:07,965 --> 00:03:08,906
Well, no.

55
00:03:09,547 --> 00:03:12,950
Lore is not the only solution to giving your character

56
00:03:13,010 --> 00:03:13,911
a strong background.

57
00:03:14,591 --> 00:03:16,893
The reason your character doesn't necessarily

58
00:03:16,953 --> 00:03:20,537
need more lore is that you will never, ever,

59
00:03:21,626 --> 00:03:26,891
ever be able to turn them into a complete, three-dimensional character with all the memories

60
00:03:26,951 --> 00:03:31,195
and history of a sentient being without living out their entire lifetime.

61
00:03:31,936 --> 00:03:36,521
You couldn't even write the full lore for a baby, because its life is going on at the

62
00:03:36,561 --> 00:03:37,422
same rate as yours.

63
00:03:39,090 --> 00:03:43,654
You can try, but I don't know how much fun you're going to have, or how much fun your

64
00:03:43,694 --> 00:03:44,355
audience will have.

65
00:03:44,895 --> 00:03:46,817
So let's just not write for babies.

66
00:03:47,157 --> 00:03:52,422
Anyway, this is a screenshot from Batman Arkham City, with a bio for one of Batman's most

67
00:03:52,642 --> 00:03:54,764
timely foes, Calendar Man.

68
00:03:55,265 --> 00:04:00,189
We will never know enough about Calendar Man, though the masses may beg for more of him.

69
00:04:01,185 --> 00:04:06,090
Now we could get together and give him loads and loads of backstory, and it might please

70
00:04:06,210 --> 00:04:08,272
a few hardcore Calendar Man fans.

71
00:04:08,813 --> 00:04:10,414
Raise your hands if you're in that group.

72
00:04:10,674 --> 00:04:14,278
But very few people are actually going to dig into that lore.

73
00:04:15,039 --> 00:04:17,602
You might find it important, and maybe it is.

74
00:04:17,742 --> 00:04:20,224
Maybe it's vital information for this character's backstory.

75
00:04:20,264 --> 00:04:22,006
But how does your audience know that?

76
00:04:22,667 --> 00:04:26,688
You're just telling them facts. Facts, in this case, about Calendar Man.

77
00:04:27,208 --> 00:04:32,369
I mean, the guy based his identity upon calendars. Is lore going to do much for this poor lost soul?

78
00:04:33,509 --> 00:04:40,371
So you can convey lore without telling. Lore provides explicit characterization, but the

79
00:04:40,471 --> 00:04:45,192
often easier and more rewarding route is through implicit characterization.

80
00:04:46,292 --> 00:04:49,333
So what is implicit characterization, you ask?

81
00:04:49,697 --> 00:04:54,805
Well, it's basically any context that we can pick up without being explicitly told.

82
00:04:55,547 --> 00:04:59,413
We can get implicit characterization most clearly through visuals.

83
00:05:00,114 --> 00:05:03,339
Through character art, we can pick up an incredible amount of information.

84
00:05:04,044 --> 00:05:06,605
This is a character from Luga's hit game, June's Journey.

85
00:05:06,866 --> 00:05:09,087
Without reading a line of text, you

86
00:05:09,127 --> 00:05:11,828
can tell me probably a good amount about this character.

87
00:05:12,508 --> 00:05:13,789
Without seeing her character brief,

88
00:05:13,829 --> 00:05:16,090
you can tell me about her general attitude,

89
00:05:16,490 --> 00:05:20,332
her social class, her age, where she might be from,

90
00:05:20,592 --> 00:05:22,333
and how her moods manifest themselves.

91
00:05:22,854 --> 00:05:26,936
This is all right here on the page in the form of her,

92
00:05:27,376 --> 00:05:31,978
how she dresses, the expressions on her face, her general style,

93
00:05:32,098 --> 00:05:33,219
and her body positioning.

94
00:05:34,082 --> 00:05:39,767
But we can learn similar things from voices, and they can help us with our dialogue, just like visuals.

95
00:05:40,889 --> 00:05:42,951
But my dialogue is already pretty good, you say.

96
00:05:43,551 --> 00:05:49,037
Well, how do you know that your dialogue is good? Have you heard it out of your character's mouth?

97
00:05:50,178 --> 00:05:57,305
I came across this tweet a while ago by Mike Bethel of Thomas Was Alone fame, and I had to save it. It resonated with me.

98
00:05:58,092 --> 00:05:58,473
He wrote,

99
00:05:59,216 --> 00:06:03,672
My writing gets ten times better once I've settled on my dream casting for the character

100
00:06:03,712 --> 00:06:04,294
I'm working on.

101
00:06:05,352 --> 00:06:05,953
It's a good tweet.

102
00:06:06,553 --> 00:06:08,254
It's actually a really good point, too.

103
00:06:09,115 --> 00:06:11,216
Mentally assembling a cast of actors

104
00:06:11,256 --> 00:06:12,256
who could play your character

105
00:06:12,316 --> 00:06:14,318
is already providing characterization.

106
00:06:15,058 --> 00:06:16,979
Imagine you're struggling with a character,

107
00:06:17,340 --> 00:06:20,061
making their dialogue sound consistent and iconic,

108
00:06:20,121 --> 00:06:22,103
and you realize, huh, you know,

109
00:06:22,503 --> 00:06:24,504
Sylvester Stallone kind of sounds like this,

110
00:06:24,844 --> 00:06:26,905
and the dialogue starts to flow naturally.

111
00:06:26,965 --> 00:06:29,027
Well, you know, at least as naturally

112
00:06:29,147 --> 00:06:30,928
as Sylvester Stallone's dialogue does,

113
00:06:31,468 --> 00:06:33,690
because you know what he sounds like.

114
00:06:34,859 --> 00:06:39,764
That's the point. A character is much easier to solidify when you know how they sound.

115
00:06:41,145 --> 00:06:46,850
Let's talk about Super Mario. You look at him now, and you know what he sounds like.

116
00:06:47,171 --> 00:06:48,652
But it wasn't always this way.

117
00:06:49,677 --> 00:06:57,844
Mario Bros. was Mario's first self-titled game, but back in 1983, he didn't look anything like the Mario we're familiar with.

118
00:06:58,405 --> 00:07:05,451
Only with the release of Super Mario Bros. 2 in 1988 did we start to get closer to the idea of Mario that we have today,

119
00:07:05,891 --> 00:07:10,014
with the big eyes, the bulbous nose, and the squat figure that he's had ever since.

120
00:07:11,326 --> 00:07:15,912
And that was the extent of our understanding of Mario's character, which continued with

121
00:07:16,112 --> 00:07:19,536
1988's Super Mario Bros. 3 and 1990's Super Mario World.

122
00:07:19,977 --> 00:07:26,986
Now, I want you to erase everything you know about Mario and just focus on these images

123
00:07:27,666 --> 00:07:30,210
and the explicit lore that we knew at the time.

124
00:07:31,036 --> 00:07:35,060
He's a plumber, he's Italian, he jumps around a lot,

125
00:07:36,061 --> 00:07:36,922
he uses pipes.

126
00:07:37,763 --> 00:07:40,005
So what does this guy sound like

127
00:07:40,286 --> 00:07:41,947
based on purely what we see?

128
00:07:42,865 --> 00:07:49,893
Hey, I'm Mario! Hey, I'm flying! I'm riding on a dinosaur! I don't know, something like that.

129
00:07:49,913 --> 00:07:55,859
I mean, this visual was all that we knew about Mario. Unless you watched the Super Mario Brothers

130
00:07:55,900 --> 00:08:00,104
Super Show, which is maybe where I'm getting this kind of voice from. But that's all we knew

131
00:08:00,144 --> 00:08:03,247
at the time, and that is indeed all we knew about Mario until 1996.

132
00:08:05,174 --> 00:08:08,837
when Mario 64 came out, it shocked the industry.

133
00:08:09,477 --> 00:08:12,119
Not only was Mario in 3D for the first time

134
00:08:12,220 --> 00:08:15,142
with a huge array of animations, but he actually spoke.

135
00:08:15,782 --> 00:08:18,064
And that gave him instant characterization

136
00:08:18,104 --> 00:08:20,426
that not even an army of writers could provide.

137
00:08:21,587 --> 00:08:22,127
Let's listen.

138
00:08:22,968 --> 00:08:25,610
Wah!

139
00:08:25,690 --> 00:08:26,130
Boo!

140
