Thank you so much for playing my game.

188
00:09:36,350 --> 00:09:38,412
Okay, Mario, quiet down. We're not here for you anymore.

189
00:09:38,892 --> 00:09:41,014
Okay, so there's not a serious bone in Mario's body,

190
00:09:41,274 --> 00:09:44,837
and it has been a part of his characterization ever since we heard his voice.

191
00:09:45,617 --> 00:09:47,919
Even when Mario games are more narratively driven,

192
00:09:47,999 --> 00:09:50,001
such as in the Mario & Luigi series,

193
00:09:50,121 --> 00:09:52,883
Mario still expresses himself in the same way.

194
00:09:53,464 --> 00:09:57,247
We've picked up an incredible amount of information just by hearing him speak.

195
00:09:58,027 --> 00:09:58,608
And you may say,

196
00:09:59,468 --> 00:10:01,430
I don't need that. I'm not making Mario.

197
00:10:01,630 --> 00:10:01,770
Well...

198
00:10:02,779 --> 00:10:07,941
Why aren't you? Mario is as iconic a character as video games have ever made, and his voice

199
00:10:08,341 --> 00:10:10,322
is part of what makes him iconic.

200
00:10:11,222 --> 00:10:15,183
Here's another extreme example of how performance can positively affect your game.

201
00:10:15,944 --> 00:10:20,605
This is one of the most iconic characters to come out of a video game in the last decade.

202
00:10:21,666 --> 00:10:23,486
And you probably have no clue who he is.

203
00:10:24,935 --> 00:10:28,876
How about now? Do you recognize him? Yeah, that's the same guy.

204
00:10:29,376 --> 00:10:35,819
Voss from Far Cry 3 was originally your typical big ol' angry brute of a character,

205
00:10:35,919 --> 00:10:42,061
but when Michael Mando simply auditioned for the role, the character changed dramatically.

206
00:10:42,782 --> 00:10:48,984
The depth that the actor provided gave Voss nuance that he didn't have. A reason for his rage

207
00:10:49,304 --> 00:10:53,746
that not only improved the character, but altered the identity for the entire game.

208
00:10:54,719 --> 00:11:00,247
If you haven't played it—minor spoiler—Vas isn't even the main villain, but look who's

209
00:11:00,287 --> 00:11:00,968
on the cover art.

210
00:11:01,669 --> 00:11:07,537
He became the identity of the game through a strong, unsettling, nuanced performance

211
00:11:07,737 --> 00:11:09,280
that changed the writing for the character.

212
00:11:10,380 --> 00:11:15,641
And then Far Cry 4 came out with another charismatic, memorable villain driving the action.

213
00:11:16,201 --> 00:11:17,702
And it happened again in Far Cry 5.

214
00:11:18,722 --> 00:11:23,023
And it will happen once more, well probably not once more, in Far Cry 6.

215
00:11:23,103 --> 00:11:30,784
So it wasn't only one game, but an entire franchise that was uplifted by a performance

216
00:11:30,824 --> 00:11:33,765
that changed the way a studio viewed character building.

217
00:11:34,625 --> 00:11:39,486
Michael Mando, my man, I really hope you're getting royalties, cuz, damn.

218
00:11:41,005 --> 00:11:44,428
But this is all big budget craziness, you say.

219
00:11:44,909 --> 00:11:46,870
My game doesn't even have voiced characters,

220
00:11:46,950 --> 00:11:49,192
so what good is all this going to do me?

221
00:11:49,873 --> 00:11:52,815
Well, surprise, you don't even need to have

222
00:11:52,875 --> 00:11:55,537
voiced characters for performance to make a big difference.

223
00:11:56,675 --> 00:12:00,919
At Wooga, we do mobile games, and as many of you know, the number of people playing

224
00:12:00,959 --> 00:12:03,881
mobile games with sound on is really, really low.

225
00:12:04,382 --> 00:12:09,326
Whether sound is worth having on during a typical mobile game is another GDC talk that

226
00:12:09,366 --> 00:12:13,650
I'm not qualified to give, but the fact remains that the day players will routinely

227
00:12:13,690 --> 00:12:16,192
hear the sound of their mobile games is still quite far away.

228
00:12:16,933 --> 00:12:21,137
But we still weave performance into our process at Wooga on June's journey.

229
00:12:22,004 --> 00:12:24,125
This is our standard simplified process.

230
00:12:24,405 --> 00:12:29,126
Of course, we plot our overarching scenes, we write our story, we test our dialogue,

231
00:12:29,386 --> 00:12:30,246
and we implement it.

232
00:12:30,887 --> 00:12:35,288
But the testing is where we can get a lot of hints about characters and have some fun.

233
00:12:36,528 --> 00:12:37,148
This is my team.

234
00:12:37,908 --> 00:12:40,169
They're going to do a typical scene reading.

235
00:12:40,649 --> 00:12:42,130
Don't worry, it's short.

236
