Okay, you get the point.

248
00:13:30,392 --> 00:13:32,094
That's not that great.

249
00:13:32,474 --> 00:13:35,998
When you're just reading, you get maybe flubs in your dialogue.

250
00:13:36,018 --> 00:13:39,381
You may have heard that there was a little bit of a typo that was corrected,

251
00:13:39,421 --> 00:13:40,623
but that's kind of all we get.

252
00:13:41,504 --> 00:13:44,687
But you don't need to have actors in the writer's room

253
00:13:44,707 --> 00:13:46,509
to be able to put forth a performance.

254
00:13:47,029 --> 00:13:50,132
I want to start with a writer's bit.

255
00:13:51,090 --> 00:13:54,613
Sorry, I want to start with a writer's biggest strength, and that is empathy.

256
00:13:55,314 --> 00:13:59,758
Think about how your character feels on a very basic level, line by line.

257
00:14:00,358 --> 00:14:03,581
How would they react to the situation that they're facing?

258
00:14:04,622 --> 00:14:06,283
Don't be afraid to get physical.

259
00:14:06,483 --> 00:14:09,946
I'm not saying punch your colleagues in the face if that's what your character is doing,

260
00:14:10,266 --> 00:14:11,648
but go ahead and punch the air if it helps.

261
00:14:12,048 --> 00:14:12,929
Slam the table.

262
00:14:13,389 --> 00:14:17,032
Actually laugh, because this physicality gets put into character.

263
00:14:18,474 --> 00:14:19,354
Slow down.

264
00:14:19,895 --> 00:14:22,435
This isn't a script reading anymore.

265
00:14:22,575 --> 00:14:24,636
The objective isn't to get it over with.

266
00:14:25,156 --> 00:14:27,037
Give your characters the same respect

267
00:14:27,097 --> 00:14:28,677
you give them in dialogue writing.

268
00:14:29,577 --> 00:14:30,618
Finally, just have fun.

269
00:14:31,098 --> 00:14:33,438
You are being paid, hopefully,

270
00:14:33,899 --> 00:14:35,539
to do creative things for a living.

271
00:14:36,679 --> 00:14:37,239
Life is good.

272
00:14:37,660 --> 00:14:39,900
This is a justified part of the process.

273
00:14:40,320 --> 00:14:42,161
So don't feel bad about enjoying it.

274
00:14:42,961 --> 00:14:44,442
I want to play that same clip again,

275
00:14:44,482 --> 00:14:46,542
and this time, turn on a little bit of character.

276
00:14:47,355 --> 00:14:48,209
and whenever you're ready.

277
00:15:12,184 --> 00:15:16,849
I can't, I need rest. I already work all day, and I'm taking care of my grandmother.

278
00:15:17,029 --> 00:15:21,393
Oh, you poor thing. I'll make you a deal then. I can give you all the rest you need.

279
00:15:21,994 --> 00:15:25,577
I'll just cross off all your shifts and you can put those filthy little feet up.

280
00:15:25,597 --> 00:15:29,061
Sir, I need those hours. How will I pay the rent?

281
00:15:29,201 --> 00:15:30,102
That's your problem, you see.

282
00:15:35,152 --> 00:15:42,538
Alright, so we got a few benefits out of this more characterful meeting, out of this more

283
00:15:42,578 --> 00:15:45,200
characterful run-through of our dialogue.

284
00:15:45,801 --> 00:15:49,324
First, we are hearing the lines as if a human delivered them.

285
00:15:49,864 --> 00:15:51,245
Which is always a good start.

286
00:15:51,605 --> 00:15:53,607
It helps us avoid unnatural dialogue.

287
00:15:54,507 --> 00:15:56,609
We've gotten a tonal check on our work.

288
00:15:57,089 --> 00:15:59,011
Does a line sound angry enough?

289
00:15:59,211 --> 00:16:02,273
Does the character feel insulted, hurt, hangry?

290
00:16:02,833 --> 00:16:03,514
Well, we know now.

291
00:16:04,394 --> 00:16:06,996
Third, we have a possible hint at our character's background.

292
00:16:07,237 --> 00:16:08,577
You heard some accents.

293
00:16:09,318 --> 00:16:11,019
That we can use for characterization.

294
00:16:11,460 --> 00:16:13,401
We might also pick up an appropriate age.

295
00:16:13,661 --> 00:16:15,382
Maybe there's a little grit in their voice

296
00:16:15,422 --> 00:16:17,844
that speaks to a troubled childhood, or a drinking

297
00:16:17,904 --> 00:16:19,285
problem, or maybe they smoke.

298
00:16:19,706 --> 00:16:24,478
Who knows, maybe they sound like Gilbert Gottfried with all of the challenges that that entails.

299
00:16:25,419 --> 00:16:29,441
Fourth, through this characterization, we have some idea about how our characters express

300
00:16:29,461 --> 00:16:29,862
themselves.

301
00:16:30,342 --> 00:16:33,744
We can almost see in our mind's eye how they'll move when they speak.

302
00:16:34,365 --> 00:16:38,528
If you've ever seen old clips of Disney animators, they'd keep a mirror at their

303
00:16:38,548 --> 00:16:43,111
desks so that they could act out scenes to ensure that characters were making the right

304
00:16:43,131 --> 00:16:43,511
faces.

305
00:16:44,332 --> 00:16:49,336
What this all amounts to is that vocal performance gives character depth at a very slight cost

306
00:16:49,696 --> 00:16:52,058
of putting ourselves out there and getting into character.

307
00:16:53,061 --> 00:16:57,743
As a result of characterful readings, we regularly change the direction of our characters, especially

308
00:16:57,823 --> 00:16:59,064
early on in the writing process.

309
00:16:59,564 --> 00:17:04,127
They grow in complexity and personality and end up with more depth than they would in

310
00:17:04,147 --> 00:17:04,587
a vacuum.

311
00:17:05,587 --> 00:17:09,129
If you've been here at GDC before, you've probably met Sara Elmaleh.

312
00:17:09,409 --> 00:17:13,912
She's been an incredible champion for collaboration between voice actors and game developers,

313
00:17:14,352 --> 00:17:18,454
and I think she's got a fantastic example of how performance changed character for the

314
00:17:18,494 --> 00:17:19,514
better in Gears 5.

315
00:17:25,067 --> 00:17:25,927
I was getting worried.

316
00:17:26,207 --> 00:17:27,228
You didn't report back.

317
00:17:27,608 --> 00:17:30,610
Radio died, and these guys pulled me out of a jam.

318
00:17:30,870 --> 00:17:32,571
Calvary's here.

319
00:17:33,152 --> 00:17:36,074
I was brought in to play Lizzie Carmen in Gears 5.

320
00:17:36,654 --> 00:17:38,315
She started very tough, and she was always

321
00:17:38,375 --> 00:17:40,516
meant to be very tough, very durable, and kind

322
00:17:40,536 --> 00:17:41,477
of intimidating and cool.

323
00:17:42,353 --> 00:17:44,154
And as I was recording her for the single player,

324
00:17:44,314 --> 00:17:45,855
she got a bit wilder.

325
00:17:46,055 --> 00:17:47,215
She kind of had more gusto.

326
00:17:47,956 --> 00:17:50,177
The writers took that and ran with it.

327
00:17:50,457 --> 00:17:52,518
And it took on this like feedback loop feeling

328
00:17:52,558 --> 00:17:54,739
of affirmation as I was wild in these sessions

329
00:17:54,799 --> 00:17:56,880
and they added to her wildness and made her funnier.

330
00:17:56,940 --> 00:17:57,841
And I was like, yes.

331
00:17:57,901 --> 00:17:58,721
And so it was this feeling

332
00:17:58,761 --> 00:18:00,042
like you're building off of each other

333
00:18:00,182 --> 00:18:03,444
and finding a truer, purer, more instinctive,

334
00:18:03,524 --> 00:18:05,265
more elevated version of this character

335
00:18:05,785 --> 00:18:07,006
that just takes on a life of its own.

336
00:18:08,970 --> 00:18:12,854
One of the things I really like about Sarah's approach is that it is truly collaborative.

337
00:18:13,174 --> 00:18:16,918
Writers are fueled by her perspective and her understanding of character from a vocal

338
00:18:16,978 --> 00:18:20,902
performance perspective, and that bond creates a better end product.

339
00:18:21,783 --> 00:18:23,664
Oops, let me, okay, there we go.

340
00:18:24,004 --> 00:18:25,325
So I wanna talk a little bit more

341
00:18:25,365 --> 00:18:26,805
about that bonding aspect.

342
00:18:27,285 --> 00:18:30,726
Most of us can recognize when writing is uninspired

343
00:18:30,806 --> 00:18:32,387
or when it's done just to fulfill

344
00:18:32,447 --> 00:18:33,967
some sort of narrative checkbox.

345
00:18:34,568 --> 00:18:36,628
If your studio acts as though writing

346
00:18:36,748 --> 00:18:38,969
is just the thing one must do to push the player along,

347
00:18:39,329 --> 00:18:42,090
it is up to you to bring that enthusiasm for writing.

348
00:18:42,150 --> 00:18:44,831
And the best way to do that is really to have fun with it.

349
00:18:45,291 --> 00:18:47,452
This is my team again, this time reading a scene

350
00:18:47,832 --> 00:18:50,033
where a parrot holds the answer to a mystery.

351
00:18:51,504 --> 00:18:59,030
That's my money, I'll give you the right to it!

352
00:18:59,070 --> 00:19:01,912
You're quite the talker, aren't you, Mooty?

353
00:19:02,572 --> 00:19:04,794
You're French, man!

354
00:19:04,994 --> 00:19:06,635
No, you are French, this is correct.

355
00:19:06,655 --> 00:19:08,517
I was trying to say it, but...

356
00:19:08,677 --> 00:19:10,838
It was just through me.

357
00:19:10,958 --> 00:19:14,381
That's my money, I'll give you the right to it!

358
00:19:14,881 --> 00:19:16,502
You're quite the talker, aren't you, Mooty?

359
00:19:16,542 --> 00:19:18,564
Get your filthy hands off me!

360
00:19:19,097 --> 00:19:22,379
Let's see if you can find that little guy something to eat.

361
00:19:22,399 --> 00:19:24,519
Okay, you get it. This is just us having a good time.

362
00:19:24,760 --> 00:19:27,221
But that good time helps us bond as a team,

363
00:19:27,281 --> 00:19:30,462
which is certainly a good thing to have in your writer's room.

364
00:19:31,002 --> 00:19:33,423
The comfort that comes with a strong bond

365
00:19:33,463 --> 00:19:37,665
allows you to explore and find a character's unique voice.

366
00:19:38,005 --> 00:19:40,186
And voice makes your characters unique.

367
00:19:40,986 --> 00:19:43,507
My holy grail for written dialogue

368
00:19:43,647 --> 00:19:46,028
is for the reader to know exactly who is speaking

369
00:19:46,408 --> 00:19:47,209
without a name tag.

370
00:19:47,929 --> 00:19:53,512
Kreia from Star Wars Knights of the Old Republic 2 is one of my favorite written characters in all

371
00:19:53,532 --> 00:20:00,094
of video games. Her dialogue is impressive and nuanced and, most importantly, there's no line

372
00:20:00,114 --> 00:20:03,076
that she speaks that could be said by any other character in the game.

373
00:20:03,916 --> 00:20:08,958
She's expertly voiced by Sarah Kestelman, whom you will know from absolutely nothing.

374
00:20:09,358 --> 00:20:13,800
Unless you're an avid fan of the Royal National Theatre and the Royal Shakespeare Company,

375
00:20:13,940 --> 00:20:17,741
and although I can't confirm that her performance influenced the writing,

376
00:20:18,242 --> 00:20:20,722
it's hard to imagine it didn't. Let's hear a clip.

